        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6744.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from George Bentham, 10 May 1869</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6734.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from George Bentham, 7 May 1869</ref> and nn. 2 and 4.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2357.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Joseph Dalton Hooker</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref> 1: 365–6.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">CD enclosed the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6662F.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Fritz Müller, 14 March 1869</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">Müller’s letter was read at a meeting of the <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2944.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Linnean Society</ref> on 3 June 1869, and appeared in the <hi rend="italic">Journal of the Linnean Society</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Botany</hi>) 11 (1871): 472–4.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f7">CD refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3589.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Daniel Oliver</ref>. The Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, Inwards book, 1869, p. 147, No. 142, records the receipt of ‘Seeds of Begonia spe. semperflorens / with monstrous flowers’ from Müller via CD.</note>
